  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Co-ownership of property works well when all owners agree. When one owner wants to sell and another refuses, it creates a situation that can feel like a deadlock. The good news is that Queensland law provides several paths through it, ranging from a negotiated private resolution to a court order that compels a sale regardless of the other owner's wishes. Understanding your options early, and taking the right steps in the right order, can save significant time and legal cost.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When does this situation arise?</h2>
      <p>The most common scenarios involve a relationship breakdown where both parties own the family home and cannot agree on whether to sell or what to do with the property; an inherited property where one beneficiary wants to convert their share to cash but other beneficiaries want to hold; and investment properties owned by business partners or friends whose interests have diverged over time.</p>

      <p>Regardless of the circumstances, the legal starting point is the same. Neither co-owner can unilaterally sell the whole property without the other's consent. Both registered owners must sign the contract of sale for a valid transfer to occur. If one owner refuses to sign, the property cannot be sold through the normal process, but the law provides remedies.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Joint tenancy versus tenants in common</h2>
      <p>Co-owners hold their interest in one of two ways: as joint tenants or as tenants in common. In a joint tenancy, both owners hold the property as a single unified interest, which means if one owner dies, their share passes automatically to the surviving owner regardless of what the deceased's will says. Tenants in common each hold a separate, defined share of the property, which can be an equal split or any other proportion, and each owner can deal with their share independently through their estate.</p>

      <p>The distinction matters for a dispute. A joint tenant can sever the joint tenancy, converting their interest to a tenancy in common, without the other owner's consent. This does not allow them to sell the property unilaterally, but it does change the nature of the co-ownership and has implications for estate planning. A solicitor can explain how severance works and whether it is relevant to your situation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option 1: negotiate a buyout</h2>
      <p>If one owner wants out and the other wants to stay, a buyout is often the most efficient resolution. One owner purchases the other's share at an agreed price, which requires an independent valuation of the whole property. The buying owner then pays the selling owner their proportional share of that value, typically with their existing share of any mortgage refinanced into their name alone.</p>

      <p>The key to making this work is an agreed valuation process. Commissioning a single independent valuation that both parties accept, or having each party obtain a valuation and splitting the difference, takes the argument about price out of the negotiation. What remains is the mechanics of the transfer, which a conveyancer can manage once both parties have agreed in principle.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option 2: agree to sell and divide the proceeds</h2>
      <p>Where neither party wants to retain the property, or where a buyout is not financially viable, both owners can agree to sell on the open market and divide the net proceeds according to their ownership shares. This is the cleanest outcome and typically produces the best financial result because a properly run open-market campaign achieves a better price than a private settlement between owners under time pressure.</p>

      <p>Even where the relationship between co-owners is strained, this option is worth pursuing through solicitors before moving to court action. Legal representatives on each side can sometimes reach a sale agreement that the owners themselves cannot, and the cost of solicitor-facilitated negotiations is considerably lower than contested Supreme Court proceedings.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option 3: partition application to the Supreme Court of Queensland</h2>
      <p>If negotiation fails entirely, any co-owner can apply to the Supreme Court of Queensland for a partition order. This is a well-established legal mechanism that gives the court the power to resolve a co-ownership dispute that the owners cannot resolve themselves.</p>

      <p>The court has two options. It can order a physical partition of the land, which means dividing the land itself between the owners. In practice, this is rare for residential property because most suburban blocks cannot be divided into two separately useful parcels. The more common outcome is an order for the property to be sold and the proceeds divided between the owners according to their respective shares.</p>

      <p>The court will generally order a sale unless there are compelling reasons not to. One owner's unwillingness to sell, or a preference to wait, is not by itself a compelling reason. Courts in Queensland have consistently held that a co-owner cannot effectively veto a sale indefinitely when another co-owner has a legitimate need to realise their interest.</p>

      <p>A partition application takes time and costs money in legal fees. But for a co-owner who has exhausted negotiation options, it is a reliable path to resolution, and the costs of the application can sometimes be recovered from the other party depending on the circumstances.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Where family law applies</h2>
      <p>If the co-ownership dispute arises from the breakdown of a marriage or de facto relationship, the Federal Circuit and Family Court of Australia has concurrent jurisdiction alongside the Queensland Supreme Court, and in most cases it is the more appropriate forum. Under the Family Law Act 1975, the family court can make property orders that include compelling one party to sign a transfer or to consent to a sale. These orders carry real consequences for non-compliance.</p>

      <p>Separation involving co-owned property is almost always better handled through family law proceedings than through a standard partition application, because the family court can consider the full financial circumstances of both parties rather than treating the property in isolation. A family lawyer rather than a property solicitor is the right first call in this situation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Practical steps when a co-owner refuses to cooperate</h2>
      <p>Document all communications with the co-owner, including any requests to sell and any responses received. This record matters if the dispute escalates to a court application and the question of whether you attempted genuine negotiation becomes relevant.</p>

      <p>Obtain a formal property valuation before you negotiate. Having an independent number in hand makes it harder for the other party to stall by disputing price, and it gives you a clear basis for any buyout discussions.</p>

      <p>Engage a solicitor early. In many cases, a formal letter from a solicitor to the co-owner, setting out the legal options clearly and proposing a reasonable resolution, is enough to prompt movement. People who have been avoiding a conversation often respond differently once they understand that the other party has taken legal advice and is prepared to proceed to a court application if necessary. The cost of that letter is a fraction of the cost of litigation, and it resolves a meaningful proportion of these disputes without going further.</p>

